\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid7885863 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I was eight and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Then you came to Daybrook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Daybrook. Yes, to Daybrook here. Up agen the Daybrook church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did you move after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well, we came to - Peter's Row, which is now - where the houses stood is the - home, Goodwood Home, for the o
ld people. It all used to be - long row of - of - frame shop windows you know and that, well - then it was all went up the yard and a little shop at the bottom and - and - and we lived up the - up second house up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What age were you when you went there, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Now let me see. Let me think it out now. Oh - I wasn't - I remember having me twenty-first birthday up Peter's Row. So I should say I'd be about - seventeen or eighteen. Yes, because they asked where we lived. It wasn't - onl
y - you know, a little room. Well then - me - dad got - this house up Peter's Row and that was much bigger. Yes, well it - because, yes - there were - there was two sisters - three sisters of us and me brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did you move from Peter's Row?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Down to - Watkin's Cottage, yes. The house by itself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Why did you make that move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - the copper was outside - where we lived up there. And it was really - in bad weather it was a big lot for mother. At first - they used to have to have a - a bi
g iron - pan like that, with handle on, and a bar across the fire and boil all the - sheets and things over there. And - me dad said soon as ever he could make a move he would. Where there was a copper inside. So of course we came from there - down here -
 down to - this house. After I was twenty-one, yes, that I came there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How long did you stay in there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 'Til I was married. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So each move you made was a nicer house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you know why they came from Bulwell to Arnold?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - my - father - had a very bad illness, and he worked at the furnace, and the - they had to expose theirself, their body - everything off 'cos it was hot, and he had this bad illness - for a long time, and - doctor told him - that - he 
advised him - to get a - another job, he said, I - don't - like you going back again Mr Kerr, I - my name was Kerr before I was married, and he said - because if you go - he says - you'll have - you'll have the same trouble again. And it may be for the wo
rst. So of course with that - my dad came - to Daybrook here, when he got we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
l and strong. And he got - a job at the brewery. And he was there - at the brewery - how many years was it, forget now. I think he left - before his retirement. Yes, he left before
 his retirement, and he went to - work on the - the road, sweeping. Yes. And then - after that - he got a job at the - laundry after he retired. And he went to the Daybrook laundry, sweeping up and doing there And he - he finished his - time there, over -
 he was seventy - about seventy - seventy-five or six, and the other part, he finished doing his garden at home and all that work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So most of his working life he was at the brewery was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, yes. Yes, he was most of his life was at brewery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you know what he called himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He was on the - wagon, drays, delivery. Delivering the - you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 much to do with horses in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, he did. Yes. He drove a - what they call a float first, one horse. And th
en - after that - he had a dray with two horses. See? And he used to have to take stuff then, with the horse and dray, right out - to Shirebrooks, Sutton, Sutton in Ashfield, Kirkbank, and all - yes, all that - he used to call 'em long journeys. And they 
used to go to - Purgeton and all - all round you know, these long journeys used to take 'em all - a good day to go and all. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When he was doing this did he also do any other casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No. He just had - that like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
No, I don't think I did. No, because - when he left the brewery - oh he had a broken thigh - while he were in brewery, top of the street here, he - slipped off of the - step of the dray, and the wheel catch
ed him and then he had a broken thigh. That was what they called the Poplars then where the - the carters and the garage there, bottom of the street, yes, that used to be the Poplars. And - it was there where it was done. And then he was in the hospital, 
and then he went to the general hospital, well I think that's the only time I can remember him - was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 At Bulwell when you say he had to change his job, was he ill a long time that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I was young, but me mother said - told me, yes, me moth
er told us a lot and there's lots we knew - when we was growing up, and me being the oldest - see, so - anyway up - I think - just that little bit - no, I don't think I ever - him ever being out only that. Then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Can you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He was eighty-four when he died and he was born on Sept - September the seventh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He died at eighty-four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How long ago did he die?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 About - that's in here, both mother's and his'n. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Bulwell. Yes. Always lived there. You see, my - my grandma, that's my father's mother - she was married three times. She had three husbands. She said that she didn't have any luck with either - any of them. And - my father was born - with
 the - third father. Kerr. There was Watson - Bark and Kerr. Now we've got them brothers. Well - in the time - as she married Watson - Mr Watson, she lived up - at - somewhere near the church. Now this is what - me mother told - told me. And - she married
 
a Watson. Up - they lived up there for a while. A time, I think he was a - a stockinger, and - I think - he died, and she came then - to her own place, at Bulwell, and lived with one of her sons that wasn't married. She came to live - up Hazel Street. Wel
l
 - that was Bulwell. Well - she - she was there for a while then she married - a Burke, and then - he had a bad illness and he died. Then he left her a widow again. And - third husband was Kerr. And me - me dad was born by the third. Yes. So he was - they
 were like those were all stepbrothers to him. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How many brothers and sisters did you have, you said you were the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I had - there was - me, my sister's died and - me young sister. Me youngest sister's seventy. And a brother, and me brot
her's been - was buried recently this year. Yes. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You came first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was your next sister much younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Three years parted us. Three year parted - another - the - the second sister - to me brother, there was three more years. Ye
s. And so after - came - after me brother, him, there was six year parted me brother - and me youngest sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Can we work out how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Don't know - wait a minute. Well I was - married in - February the - I don
't know exactly how old she were born. No, I - I - I don't think I quite got that. I should say she'd be about - twenty-two. Twenty-two I think or three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did she strike you as about the same age as your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, well - she was eighty-four - when she died and - she died in - let me put it this way, perhaps I can put it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 She was eighty-four as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. She lived eighteen month after me dad. And - she died September the thirtieth, 1951.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So they weren't very far apart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, they wasn't. No they wasn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did she came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Same place. Bulwell. Yes. She used to work in the mill. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was she always in the mill before she was married or did she have several sorts of jobs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, only that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you know what her occupation was exactly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Oh no. I think it was lace - more than anything, in the - more on the lace side. There's so many different jobs in the - that's right, that's what I'm just thinking. Oh yes, she - she used to say like - how
 they used to - have the lace you know, and - and hold it and do it. Bring it through. She used to tell us about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 She didn't say which her special job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 It was that. At - at the mach - bank - the machinery you know. Yes, bringing it - yes, through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Some people separated lace into strips from the big wide bits, did she do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Yes. Yes, well - it's outdoors work, I've done many a lot of that. I have when I were at school, and mother took - mother used to do it at home. Because 
they used to have to take it and fetch it. Drawing and clipping and scalloping. Yes. Drawing, and clipping - the - end bits off of the lace, and then the scalloping. Mother used to do all that. And we used to have to do the drawing. For her. And she would
 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What age did you do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh I wasn't going to school then. Oh yes, perhaps about - about ten or eleven, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you know if she carried on with her job at the mill after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No. No, she never did. No, because you see - it was - I was on the way. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you know when you were first born whether she did any part time work like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No. She didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When did she start taking in the lace, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 That was when we came - to her, Arnold, Daybrook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When you were about eight and a half?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 That's right, yes, and - she did seaming as well, Mr Partridge up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Redhill, and we used to have to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 She did that at home as well did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. And we used to have to do the rib, while mother
 done the feet and the - toes. See. Seaming, and - we used to have to fetch it and take it, and - bring some more back. So - that was how it was with us. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When you were a bit bigger did she ever go out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, never. Never. She always - you know, was at home to look after us, and cook, clean, and make and do. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You mostly lived at Watkins cottage in your childhood was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, we - lived on the hill when I went to school, and I was going out to work when we went up to Peter's
 Row. And - I'd just about started out to work then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So how many rooms were there in that other house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
In the terraced house there was - there was a little place what you - did your work in and that you know, your sink and that. Then there was j
ust a little living room, and there was only two rooms up, the front bedroom and the back bedroom but they was very small. Very small. They was then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 In this part of the world do they have a special word for where you do all your work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well there - they might call it the kitchen. And in - the olden days they used to say the scullery. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 A friend come from Lancashire and - she always calls it the house place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes. Yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Would you know what she meant by that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, 
yes, I should. That is where you go and do all the - we - call it the kitchen. Yes. Of course they've altered a lot of the names. You see, in the old days - it was the kitchen, then it was the - the - house, used to call it the house, then that was the fr
o
nt you see, call that the front, this was the - this was the - house place. Then front, that was the kitchen where you did all your work, your washing and that you see. Well then - of course - some people, there was the - sitting room, the lounge and all 
that. Well that's entirely gone now. You see, it's all - all different, all the - different names for it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did anyone else besides your parents and brother and sisters live in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, no one. No, nobody, just the family of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You didn't have anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
No. She did it all her herself. She did her - all her own baking - and cooking of every kind, her jam, must be - must be - have the jams made, and we must have the wine made. Elderberry wine - elderberry wine
, parsnip wine - beetroot wine - and must have them done. And - used to do all that. Raspberry vinegar. Blackcurrant vinegar. And Elderberry wine. The jars and - all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did you keep all this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Used to keep it in one bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was the washing done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. Yes, the washing was all done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your mother or father}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 make or mend the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Me - dad used to - he used to mend our shoes. And me mother used to do the mending and she used to make clothes - for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Were the clothes new or second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - she - turned and twisted them about. And anything as she could make - anything out of for us she did. That's how she worked it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did she get them from in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well there was perhaps - something that good - skirts of her own and - all like that as she made little dresses for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did she ever buy new thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes, she bought new things, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where were they bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well we used to go to - to town. 
And - the one - now I'm just going to tell you. We used to have to go to the town every Saturday with my mother - to Broadens, to fetch butter. And everything. And then go down - to Wheatley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645 
\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 s and fetch a - a leg of lamb, or a shoulder. And you did get it 
- for them days, you'd be surprised - what you got for - for a leg of lamb - if you'd got four and six. Beautiful. And - other bits of things. Well then we should go on to Burton, she'd get her butter. And of course margarine. She didn't buy that, I'll ad
mit she didn't. That was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence a pound. But the best butter was ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence then it was Danish. She used to bring that. And the sugar. That was three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 ha'pence a pound - that was. Sugar in them days. And if you - took - three pound you got a pound extra. And - the best lard - was sixpence a pound, three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence for half. And - bacon - that bacon was about ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence, and you got lovely - bacon, yes, and then the - the - ham you know, the shoulder and all like that, that all come - under much cheaper than the 
price what you have to pay for now. Double and treble. But it used to be beautiful stuff. And - of course most mothers used to go down town, well then from here to get to it, we had to walk to Carrington, to get the horse trams, yes. Yes. Carrington churc
h
. And we - and it - there were two buses route from Arnold. Mr Bradbury's, and Mr Kerr. Well there was people on, filled up, when they got down here you couldn't get on. You'd got to set off and walk to Carrington, catch the horse tram, that was a penny o
n
 them. In them days, to take you right to Victoria Station. Then we used to cut through there for the - to get the meat, then come back - to Burton and get all the groceries there. Well then when we come back - if the bus was in again the milk and bread -
 used to be - that was in there, and there was - there was room for us we got in, and then we come straight to just -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 All the way home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. And put us out again where we wanted. But if it was full well - we'd got to go on the - bus ride again. 
And - that's how we used to have to work it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your mother go and shop in Nottingham because it was better value or weren't there many shops here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - yes, there was a nice few shops here but they were very small shops. But they got be
tter stuff, see, it was a big place Burtons which it is now. Of course it's - splendid place now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So if she'd any clothes buying she'd do it on a Saturday in Nottingham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. And we used to go to - Coman's or Battle and Barclay - for dress mater
ial. Yes. Well it was a - we used to go there, and you could get dress - beautiful dress material for one and eleven a yard. Two and eleven it was - splendid. An wear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your mother ever buy clothes or material to make things with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes. She
'd buy the clothes and she bought the material. And Mrs Shelton as lived on Church Drive - made our dresses. And we used to have one every year, but you couldn't put it on - every day, you must have a - a dress and a coat - Sunday wear - put away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When did you get this new, was it a birthday present or a Christmas present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well it was in midsum - in midsummer. Always - used to see that we was - you know, sort of we'll say - with a - new everything. Shoes and everything. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 And you were the oldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. And then we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So you probably didn't have passed on things quite the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I didn't. Didn't get so much as the others got. But still we'd always got - good shoes and - and well kept.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did the shoes come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 We used to go up to Mr Radford's at Front Street, where the television shop is now. Mr Radford, used to keep - a boot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 shop there. And - every time - me dad made a bit of what he called - you know - get - getting the empty cases in and the bottles, b
ringing them back and they used to allow 'wm so much on empties, and if he made a - a nice bit on empties, he used to save that money, and then he used to go - give me mother the money and he used to take us all - to Mr Radford and get us shoes there. And
 that used to pay for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So did you all have new shoes or were they sometimes second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, new shoes. I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 And your father mended them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He used to mend them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - he - he was always - gardening. That was his - hobby. Gardening and seeing as we had plenty of vegetables - potatoes and all that. It was a very big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14380001\charrsid12715645 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 arden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he do any of these other jobs, cleaning in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, he didn't - I can't remember. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, he has - he - he has done washing up at times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes, I - yes, and always fetching the coal up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, no decorating, mother always decorated. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well of course the - landlord - landlord had them done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Improvements to the house, was that the landlord as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well the landlord you see, they used to have them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he ever dress the children when they were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, he didn't ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Undress them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 If - if - sort of - you know, putting nightdresses on and taking us to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Bath you ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When me mother were busy sewing. And that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he bath you ever do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, me mother always used to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, there has been some times when he's - he's - he's - done a bit of reading to us. And explained things to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He always used to tell us stories about - different things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Were they make up stories or about his childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well, yes, I think more of make - make up stories. And he had - he has told us - that - his mother - was very strict, and - she wouldn't have him out late or anything. And 
she would make them go to Sunday school like as he made us go. She wouldn't have them running the street. And my parents never would. We had strict orders. You go to church, Sunday school, in a - a Sunday morning. You walk from Daybrook - school there, th
e
y had it there, they brought us straight up to church in two and two you know, walking, to the service to the twelve o'clock. Then you had to go home, you was told to come home 'cos of dinner. And then again at two o'clock you'd got to be back down there 
-
 for the afternoon then, and you - got a - a - a card with a - a star on if you went, and we used to have to learn what they call - the collect, that was in the prayer book. And if we said them we got one extra if we learnt it and said it. And we used to 
have to say it to the Sunday school teacher, Miss Malcross.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was that two stars, one for morning and afternoon or only one for both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 We used to get one in the morning and one in the afternoon. And if you said your collect, had learnt it and you c
ould say it to the - to Miss Malcross - she'd give you an extra - mark for it. And then - when we came out of Sunday school, it was home again ready for tea. And washed and ready again - to go to the evening service at six o'clock. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Three times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Yes. Straight out of church at eight o'clock, home, and you had it to do, if you didn't you knew what - you knew what it was. Up the stairs. Go to bed. You're not - you'll not go out no more. That was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your father ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Yes, he used to take us to garden and - and that. We used to have to - set the potatoes, we used to have to set potatoes. And we used to have to get up in the morning when it was light morning, take the barrow, and go and get it full o
f leaves. For the garden. To make what you call compost. And that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your father ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, I used to have to stand on a stool, flat stool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How old would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Oh I should think - I shouldn't be above - nine or ten. And - have what they call - it was like four wooden legs, one at - hole in the centre, and it's what
 they call a - the - bobbin stool for the spinning - of hosiery - cotton. And - it was one of me - grandmother's - husbands had, and he was in the - the hosiery trade - like the old fashioned, you know, used to work these to make stockings with you know. 
Well that's where that little stool came from, it was his - his stool. And we used to have to stand on there - and ponch. Yes, we had it to do. And - it was totally different to what it is now. They don't know they're living.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 This is the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Every week. Monday. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Before school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Yes. Used - me dad used to get up and put the copper on, and - you know, get all the water hot and then ready for mum to start, before we went to school which you used to have to get up, wash us and do, 
and have our breakfasts, and then go and - do - ponching then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How many years did you have to do this for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - no, not - exactly right through. You see, as I got older - of course I had a bit more - to - then in the - doing all the errands and all that, and - they - let it go at that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you remember when you stopped helping with the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Oh I did. I remember stopping at that. And then I used to - have to go - there was elderly people in them days used to want - the - you kn
ow, someone to go errands so they used to come and ask - me mother, and she used to say, yes, she can go. And mother used to say, now you bef careful - what you do, and watch your money. And - she said, don't take anything off of the old people. You're no
t
 to do it, she say, and if I know you take anything then I shall make you take it back. So we never did, we had it to do. It were like neighbourly you know, and we - she never allowed us to take anything, nor me d-ad didn't. It must be done without that. 
Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What other jobs did you do at home to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - we had to do the errands. We had to clean me dad's - shoes. Clean all our own shoes. And have them all set ready - for putting on clean Sunday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How did you work out between you who cleaned your dad's shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh well, I had them to do for a long while.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Because you were the eldest was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, I - I - being the eldest got it - got a lot of it. But still - never mind, we smile through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you remember when you passed that job on to one of the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Yes, me sister used to do it. And - and me brother did it for a bit. And then of course - when we get - got older you know, as they - thought they were and that, it had got - passed on and me dad used to do his
 own then, there was only me dad's to do, we always used to have to clean our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When did you stop cleaning dad's, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I think I should be about - twelve - when I stopped that because - there was business people in them days - as
 often asked - your parents - that kept a shop if - if you - if they could let them come - and scrub the cellar steps and do a little bit of scrubbing. Well - Mrs Allan at top of street, because - Mrs - it was - Flower before she was married, she kept the
 shop at top of the street on the - left hand side as you go up, and - I used to go there. It was all the knives and forks, and all them little jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well I was - I should be - I should - be about twelve - then. Well, and I used to get nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence for that. Nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
pence you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How long did it take you to earn your nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well of course you had to keep going. As soon as you'd done one job - of course he used to call you by your name then, now Annie will y
ou do this for me? I sa yes. And that, and of course we were always taught how to clean and how to - to do it properly. Them days. And I - used to get nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 pence for going - and doing that, every Friday. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What would you do, a couple of hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well it - it might - yes, it would do, yes, it did, and that. I used to know it to do all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What about the jobs your brother and sisters had in the home? Was there a difference between girls and boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - me sister next to me - she was 
rather - one for sewing - and music. She played violin and she played the piano. And - she was always - making dolls clothes. She was very very handy with that and the machine. She was often - often sewing, and piano. And - violin. She used to go down to 
Mr Smith's to learn the - violin. And - Mr - what's the name now, what was his name, he used to come into Bell's at - it was the Post Office then. Mr Borwn. She used to go there for lessons. And that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did she get out of helping in the house because she did these other things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well, she used to do bits like, dust and do and - knives and forks to do. And in those days you see - you hadn't got - lino and carpet, it was - it was white as the driven snow. We had them - we had them - them - them to scr
ub, in their turn. Knives and forks to do in your turn. You all got your work cut out. Yes. That's how we used to have to do it. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What did the boy do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well me brother - he - he used to go around taking posts then, and he - he - they did use
d to give 'em a bob or so in a week. Of course posts were only a ha'penny then. And that. And he used to - so many a week, to take the Post. Well he used to do that and then he used to have to go and help out at the garden, 'til he was ready for work.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your brother help in the house before or didn't boys in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, he didn't do - he didn't do - much in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did he help your father with the fires or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, the garden and all like that, yes. Yes, he went to do - all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did the older ones help the younger ones with things they found difficult, or look after them in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, I had to look after the - them - brother and all them, I used to have to take them out and that. And - when I was holidaying
 from school - we used to have to do so much work and then - go and play with the - brother and that. See, you used to have to go together. And me youngest sister we used to carry in the pram. And - we had strict orders not to leave the pram nor the child
, and - mind where you go. And don't go too far away. And be very careful, that was always your orders, and take them away and play, and that, while my mother used to do - other jobs, while we'd gone. And that, we used to pass that on - all on to us.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What time was it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - we used to have to be in bed be half past seven and then you - then as you got older it were a more little bit late but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, me mother always did it. She were always a - mother that was with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh I - as I got older and - and - and that I used to go to bed with the others like.
 When I got older and that I might have got told I could stay up a bit later. And then go to bed you know, about half an hour later then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did you share a bedroom or a bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, we did. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Who did you sleep with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 I - me o
ld - me sister next to me. Then me young sister used to have a little - bed - single bed, and - then me brother - had a single bed in the top room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You had one at the back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, yes, at the very top, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 And your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 And they had the - front - room, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Do you remember we were discussing the arrangements in your home about bedrooms. What happened about baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 About what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Baths. Did you have a tin bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh we had tin baths. Those big ones you know. Yes. We used to take it down the cellar, when we'd done with it and dry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 it out, and then bring it up - and - we used to - stay up - late at night after the others had gone to bed, and - bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 In front of the kitchen fire?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. Yes, in the kitche
n - oh, kitchen fire. 'Course there weren't the baths then you know. Not the Arnold Bath - not at all. You'd got to - every - about everybody had one of those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You kept yours down in the cellar, not on the outside wall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh no, down in the cellar, on the - slab. Mother did, and - that's how we used to all have to do it. And that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 How often did you have these baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well used to have one every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was it a special day always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - we'll say - mother'd gone out shopping, us
ed to draw the curtains, and have a bath whilst she'd gone. Used to have to do it like that. Then the - other - used to finish at night. Well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645 then parents used to have theirs}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645  at the week - towards the weekend like, and that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was it about once a week for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Oh yes, once a week, and then the - and - you know, you used to always wash yourself - in the morning before you got dressed thoroughly and that and - and that. Unless you were sick, well then you might have one a bit - oftener then, bu
t - I used to have - if you was ill it were bed baths and washing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When you were little when did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh every week. And every day if you'd messed them up- The parents didn't used to leave dirty clothes abo
ut. When they washed and bathed you at night - you'd gone to bed, they washed them clothes, and get them ready - and - for - either going out or get them dry - so that they'd be - ironed and aired for the - when you wanted some more. Yes. Oh aye, we had p
lenty of clean clothes and plenty of - of baths and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Used to have it in the kitchen likely. And that used to be the scullery to go and - wash you and doing and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Were there any occasions when they ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well just occasionally, but mostly in the kitchen. And that. And the - the - front then, used to - call 'em parlours. Now that's out of date. Front rooms. Now - it's the - dining room, sitting room, lounge now isn't it. We ha
d a - what they call a - a parlour.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 She used to - cook over the fire because she didn't have a stove. All over the fire. She did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 It wasn't a range at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 It was a biggish grate, with a biggish oven in li
ke. And a little tap here for hot water - from the boiler. And that, but she always used to - all her saucepans used to go on, they used to have a bar go across - the fire, and they used to put - the saucepans with the greens, potatoes - or anything else,
 and then roast the meat in the oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 When was breakfast eaten when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - in the morning before you went to school, they wouldn't let you go without you'd had - had - something to eat, either toast - or - bread and butter, which you preferred. See it just depended what you wanted. And that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What sort of time would this have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh we had to be at school at nine. So we had to be up be eight o'clock. And that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Who was there for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh well, all of us like, was the - sisters and - me brother. And that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Would your father have had his by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, he was at work, he had to be at work - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So how did he manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 He used to take a bit of lunch with him and a mash. And he used to mas
h at work 'til he came home at dinner for his dinner. Then he went back again you know. Used to have an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 So you usually had toast or bread and butter for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What did you drink then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - either tea or - or coffee, sometimes milk. Just depend. Of course milk was much cheaper then than what it is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did you have anything different on any days, say a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Oh yes, we always got a - jelly or pineapple chunks - or - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 This was for another meal, was there anything at breakfast different for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
That were - yes, you could have a bit of bacon and - either a fried egg or a boiled egg. Or a duck egg. Duck eggs were very plentiful, I used to like them but I don't now. And - that. And - yes, cooked breakfast for Sunday and that. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Midday what would it have been on a weekday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
Well - sometimes bread and butter and marmalade we had. Or jam. Or cake. Mother made her own cake, we'd always got some cake. Sometimes she'd put you butter on, sometimes - when she thought it was new you wouldn't get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3369023\charrsid12715645  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
it on. When it was going a little bit - stale - she'd put you a bit of butter on, and that. But they'd always make you come to the table. We used to say - if you left anything, well y
ou'll have it next time. Put it before you next time. But we didn't get it, we got som}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7368700\charrsid12715645 e }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 at fresh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was your evening meal the main meal when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - for supper at night - if there was any cold potatoes they'd happen fry 'em up, and 
have some - bread and butter to them. And if we didn't have that we perhaps had a bit of cheese, something of that and a bit of bread. And if not that - we just had our milk. It just depended what - what you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 On a weekday when you were at school did you come home for a hot meal in the middle of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, at dinnertime, always a cooked dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 What sort of things would you have got then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well - we used to get - stewing meat, leg of beef or crop, stew it, baking it, mashed pot
atoes, turnip. And Yorkshire pudding. And sometimes in the winter - in the winter more so - the s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7368700\charrsid12715645 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7368700\charrsid12715645 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 
ty dumplings. Done in the gravy. And a - pigs fry. That was like liver, skirts, and all bits - you know, all of that, they like - then liked it, we used to 
have that, mother used to thicken it, and - do us. Then we had meat and potato pie. And - either a jam tart on a plate, or - mincemeat. Apple tart. She used to change about you know. Lemon curd tart. If you wanted that after you'd had your other, but when
 you'd had all that to eat you'd have no -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You said you had jelly or pineapple on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Was there anything else that was special for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Well the - it were about all that stuff in that day. She used to make a jelly. An
d - put a custard on, she'd do it that way sometimes, and then put all coconut on. Well, if you brought a friend for tea you'd - happen be there you know, you'd have that. And sometimes - they'd boil beetroot, and there'd be a dish - a glass dish with tha
t
 in. If anybody preferred it. And - cake, and it'd be little cakes or - you know, just depend how me mother used to make them. Either in a big loaf, bread tin or a - the little patty tins. There'd be them, the Sunday for you, and that, celery. Used to hav
e
 celery. And pineapples. Pineapples cubes. We - we got - we got fed - well that's all you could get in them days. It's true - oh - and we often had a - a tin of salmon you know. Well used to have one the tall tin. And we all used to have it. Children as w
ell, she used to give us - you could either have it - done in a sandwich or on your plate, a little plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 But in your family the main meal was in the middle of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 No, always a cooked dinner. Not five o'clock, no. Always a cook - at dinner 
time because - you see, we all came from school, and me - me - dad came in, we all had dinner together. Well teatime you - you know how you are when you're children, well I - I'll have a bit of bread and jam mother. And a cup of tea. Now she says, you'll 
s
tay at this table 'til you've had what you want. Stay. Don't come in asking for bread - when you've had your tea here put before you. You're not going out with it in your hands. We'd always got that. So - 'cos we - you'll not have no more 'til you have yo
ur supper. And they made you have that early, so it digested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 You told me the various things your mother made but I can't remember them all, did she bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes. Yes, always had a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7885863 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6896403 AK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11173682\charrsid12715645 Yes, and wines. Yes. Oh yes.
\par 
